<!-- The Problem -->
<section class="section" aria-label="The Problem">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 class="section-heading">The Literacy Crisis Is Real</h2>

    <div class="timeline-stats">
      <div class="timeline-stat">
        <span class="timeline-stat__number">2 in 3</span>
        <span class="timeline-stat__label">US students below grade level in reading</span>
      </div>
      <div class="timeline-stat">
        <span class="timeline-stat__number">54M</span>
        <span class="timeline-stat__label">US adults read below 6th grade level</span>
      </div>
      <div class="timeline-stat">
        <span class="timeline-stat__number">130M</span>
        <span class="timeline-stat__label">US adults with limited literacy</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="prose" style="margin-block-start: var(--space-8);">
      <p>
        A friend of mine tutors high schoolers. One of her students couldn't read. At all. Not "struggling." Not "behind grade level." An 11th grader who was completely illiterate, being pushed through a system that couldn't meet all students where they are. I'm a dad with a kid who'll be in that system soon. Those stats hit different when they're personal.
      </p>
      <p>
        This isn't a niche problem. It's a market of 54 million US adults and millions more students falling through the cracks — underserved by tools that treat accessibility as a premium feature.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- What Cocovox Does -->
<section class="section surface-alt" aria-label="What Cocovox Does">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 class="section-heading">What It Does</h2>

    <div class="grid grid--3 stagger">
      <article class="card">
        <h3 class="card__title">AI Tutoring</h3>
        <p class="card__description">
          Ask for a lesson, a quiz, flashcards, or a deep dive — Cocovox generates them on the spot. Everything adjusts to your level, from 3rd grade to grad school.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="card">
        <h3 class="card__title">Literacy First</h3>
        <p class="card__description">
          Seven lesson types. Letter recognition, phoneme blending, sight words, sentence reading. Read aloud and get instant word-by-word feedback. Spaced repetition schedules your next review.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="card">
        <h3 class="card__title">AAC: A Voice for Everyone</h3>
        <p class="card__description">
          Some people can't speak. Most AAC apps show a giant grid of words. Cocovox takes a different approach with three zones: Essential Words, Personal Vocabulary, and AI Predictions.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- AAC Deep Dive -->
<section class="section" aria-label="AAC Deep Dive">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="zone-grid">
      <div class="zone-card">
        <span class="zone-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">&#x1F3AF;</span>
        <h4 class="zone-card__title">Essential Words</h4>
        <p class="zone-card__text">
          Eight words that never move. Yes, no, help, more. Muscle memory matters — if "help" is always in the same place, you can find it without looking.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="zone-card">
        <span class="zone-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">&#x2B50;</span>
        <h4 class="zone-card__title">Personal Vocabulary</h4>
        <p class="zone-card__text">
          Words you use a lot. Star your favorites and they rise to the top. Your communication tool should know you.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="zone-card">
        <span class="zone-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">&#x1F9E0;</span>
        <h4 class="zone-card__title">AI Predictions</h4>
        <p class="zone-card__text">
          AI suggests what you might say next based on context. Connected to your calendar — math class shows math words, after school shows "snack" and "tired."
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="prose" style="margin-block-start: var(--space-8);">
      <p>
        Over 100 AI voices that actually sound human. Save presets — a classroom voice for presentations, a friends voice for lunch. Every plan includes every feature. No pro tier for accessibility.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

